         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1599">
               <p>Charles was a son of <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers1605.xml"/>Vincent
                     Perronet</persName> and <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers1598.xml"/>Charity
                     (Goodhew) Perronet</persName>. When his family aligned with Methodism in the
                     mid-<date>1740s</date>, Charles became a <seg ana="itinerancy">traveling
                     preacher</seg>, helping to form the Methodist society in
                     <placeName>Dublin</placeName>. Like his brother <persName><ptr
                        target="/persons/pers1602.xml"/>Edward</persName>, Charles was estranged
                  from the Wesley brothers by the mid-<date>1750s</date> through his advocacy of
                  separation from the Church of <placeName>England</placeName>. He spent his later
                  years in <placeName>Canterbury</placeName> with his brother. See Atmore, <hi
                     rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 327–35; Batty, <hi rend="italic">Perronet</hi>;
                     <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 876; and Vickers, <hi rend="italic"
                  >Dictionary</hi>, 270.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
